'''Oliver Baumann''' ({{IPA|de|ˈɔlivɐ ˈbaʊman}}; born 2 June 1990 in [[Breisach]]) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Bundesliga]] club [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]], where he is also [[captain (association football)|captain]], and the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].<ref name=profile>{{cite web | url = https://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/en/teams/first-team/team-en-us/einzelportraet/show/oliver-baumann | title = Steckbrief Oliver Baumann | publisher = TSG 1899 Hoffenheim | access-date = 3 August 2022}}</ref>

==Club career==
===SC Freiburg===
====Youth and B teams====
Oliver Baumann joined [[SC Freiburg]]'s youth team in 2002, since then he has gone on to make 104 [[Bundesliga]] appearances for the club. He went on to make 21 appearances for SC Freiburg.

====First team====
[[File:Oliver Baumann.jpg|upright=0.8|thumb|Baumann with Freiburg in 2013]]
On the last day of the [[2009–10 Bundesliga]] season, Baumann made his senior team debut in a 3–1 home victory over [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bundesliga 34. Spieltag: SC Freiburg – Borussia Dortmund|url=http://www.zeit.de/sport/2010-05/fussball-bundesliga-bochum-bremen/seite-4|access-date=28 June 2016|work=Zeit Online|date=8 May 2010|language=de}}</ref> He became the [[SC Freiburg]] first-choice goalkeeper from the [[2010–11 SC Freiburg season|2010–11 season]] onwards, where he made 30 appearances in the [[Bundesliga]].{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} In June 2011, he extended his contract until 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oliver Baumann verlängert beim SC Freiburg|url=http://www.badische-zeitung.de/sport/scfreiburg/oliver-baumann-verlaengert-beim-sc-freiburg--46859649.html|access-date=28 June 2016|work=Badische Zeitung|date=28 June 2011|language=de}}</ref> In the following two seasons, [[2011–12 SC Freiburg season|2011–12]] and [[2012–13 SC Freiburg season|2012–13]], Baumann made a total of 73 appearances for the Freiburg first-team, 67 of those in the league.

In the [[2013–14 SC Freiburg season|2013–14 season]] he continued to be the mainstay of the Freiburg line-up, starting all of the club's first six [[Bundesliga]] fixtures, as well as starting Freiburg's opening [[UEFA Europa League]] and [[DFB-Pokal]] matches. In a match against Hamburg SV, Baumann made three terrible bloopers that led to a 3–0 loss to Hamburg SV.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bundesliga: Freiburg keeper Oliver Baumann was positive despite 3-0 loss to Hamburg|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/16414/8996507/bundesliga-freiburg-keeper-oliver-baumann-was-positive-despite-3-0-loss-to-hamburg|access-date=28 June 2016|work=Sky Sports|date=28 October 2013}}</ref> Despite his terrible performance, he started the following game against [[1. FC Nürnberg|Nürnberg]] and kept a clean sheet to help Freiburg achieve its first win of the 2013–14 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2013/0000276414.php |title=DARIDA FIRES FREIBURG PAST SORRY NÜRNBERG |publisher=bundesliga.com |access-date=12 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913151621/http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2013/0000276414.php |archive-date=13 September 2014 }}</ref> On 24 September 2013, Baumann signed a new contract at the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=SC Freiburg verlängert vorzeitig mit Oliver Baumann|url=http://www.badische-zeitung.de/sport/scfreiburg/sc-freiburg-verlaengert-vorzeitig-mit-oliver-baumann--75520159.html|access-date=28 June 2016|work=Badische Zeitung|date=24 September 2013|language=de}}</ref>

===TSG Hoffenheim===
On 14 May 2014, Baumann joined [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]] on a four-year contract deal.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Oliver Baumann wechselt zur TSG |url=http://www.achtzehn99.de/oliver-baumann-wechselt-zur-tsg/ |work=TSG 1899 Hoffenheim |date=14 May 2014 |language=de}}</ref> He became Hoffenheim's starting goalkeeper ever since, and team captain in 2022 following the retirement of [[Benjamin Hübner]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Who are the Bundesliga's captains in 2023/24?|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/captains-2023-24-bayern-dortmund-leipzig-manuel-neuer-emre-can-24000 |website=bundesliga.com |access-date=2025-01-25}}</ref> In the [[2023–24 Bundesliga|2023–24 season]], he achieved the most saves in Bundesliga in 157 occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/stats/players/goalkeeper-saves |title=Bundesliga Stats 2023-2024: Shots saved |publisher=Bundesliga |access-date=30 May 2024 }}</ref> In August 2025, he extended his contract with the club until 2026.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/en/news/overview/2025/08/tsg-hoffenheim-prematurely-extend-captain-oliver-baumanns-contract |title=TSG Hoffenheim prematurely extend captain Oliver Baumann's contract |publisher=TSG 1899 Hoffenheim |date=1 August 2025 }}</ref> On 21 November 2025, Baumann became the 14th player in Bundesliga history since 1963 to reach 500 appearances after starting against [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=22 November 2025 |title=🔢 Bundesliga keeper reaches 500 games, only 13 beat him to it |url=https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/bundesliga-keeper-reaches-500-games-103900619.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAADJavKAWXM2iPxbsTSuD4hIibLyZrccoa0LXn8RzcJ-LLrlTr3jztvGw4DgcJqS4pihWwKSbrfKZDqHFhGt2IfZa09HpyehX1416Df4buf16dC9zsEA486SDINJMY5J-g7mAJfB5Lz3eUJy2iZvTQXsdZ-uk1xomWwB81adErC7G |access-date=22 November 2025 |website= |publisher=Yahoo! Sports}}</ref>

==International career==

Baumann made at least one appearance for each of the nation's youth sides from under-18 to under-21 level.<ref name="wf.net Int">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe131946/oliver-baumann/international-matches/ |title=Oliver Baumann: Internationals |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HeimSpiel Medien |access-date=16 October 2024}}</ref> His only [[Germany national youth football team#Germany national under-18 squad|Germany under-18]] appearance came in a 3–2 [[exhibition game#International football|friendly]] defeat to the [[Republic of Ireland national under-18 football team|Republic of Ireland]] in 2007.<ref name="wf.net Int" /> Four of his seven [[Germany national youth football team#Germany national under-19 squad|under-19]] matches were qualifiers for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2009 European Under-19 Championships]], but despite his two clean sheets in the [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship elite qualification|elite round]], Germany failed to progress.<ref name="Datencenter">{{cite web |url=https://datencenter.dfb.de/datencenter/personen/oliver-baumann/spieler |title=Oliver Baumann: Spielerprofil |language=de |trans-title=Oliver Baumann: Player profile |website=DFB Datencenter |access-date=16 October 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/news/0257-0de7a344ca0b-bc6ddbcacd62-1000--merida-sends-spain-into-finals-again/ |title=Mérida sends Spain into finals again |publisher=UEFA |date=26 May 2009 |access-date=16 October 2024}}</ref>

After making two appearances for [[Germany national under-20 football team|Germany's under-20 side]], against [[Switzerland national under-20 football team|Switzerland]] and [[Italy national under-20 football team|Italy]],<ref name="wf.net Int" /> he made the step up to under-21 level. He played once in [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification Group 5|qualifying for the 2011 European Championships]], three times in [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|2013 qualifying]], and once in the [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2013 finals]], as well as four friendlies.<ref name="Datencenter" />

Baumann was called up to [[Germany national football team|Germany's squad]] for [[UEFA Nations League]] matches against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in September 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/loew-verantwortung-gegenueber-den-spielern-218420/|title=Löw: "Ich habe Verantwortung gegenüber den Spielern"|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|date=25 August 2020|access-date=6 September 2020|language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230330054049/https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/loew-verantwortung-gegenueber-den-spielern-218420/ |archive-date=30 March 2023}}</ref> and named in the squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] on home soil,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.com/en/news/uefa-euro-2024-all-squads-and-players-full-list|title=UEFA Euro 2024: All squads and players full list|date=7 June 2024|access-date=16 October 2024|website=Olympics.com}}</ref> but did not play. He finally made his senior debut on 14 October 2024, in the starting eleven for a [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League A]] match against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] at the [[Allianz Arena]], and kept a clean sheet in Germany's 1–0 victory.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Frank|last=Mo|title="The game could not have been more perfect", Oliver Baumann reacts to dream debut for Germany in 1–0 win over the Netherlands|url=https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2024/10/15/24268938/oliver-baumann-germany-netherlands-julian-nagelsmann-manuel-neuer-marc-andre-ter-stegen-alex-nubel|work=Bavarian Football Works|date=15 October 2024|access-date=16 October 2024}}</ref> On 21 May 2026, he was selected in Germany’s 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-gibt-wm-kader-bekannt|title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann gibt WM-Kader bekannt|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|language=de|date=21 May 2026|access-date=21 May 2026}}</ref>

